{
  "executive_summary": "A lean ML serving architecture for real-time delivery time prediction, designed for a 4-person team. The system separates the hot path (feature assembly → model inference → response) from the cold path (data collection → training → evaluation → promotion). A pre-computed feature store eliminates expensive joins at inference time, keeping P99 under 100ms. Model versioning with blue-green deployment enables safe weekly retraining with instant rollback. The architecture intentionally avoids heavyweight ML platforms (Kubeflow, SageMaker pipelines) in favor of simple, ownable components that 4 engineers can operate.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Prediction API",
        "responsibility": "Synchronous HTTP/gRPC endpoint called at checkout. Accepts order features, assembles the full feature vector from the feature store, runs model inference, returns predicted minutes. Stateless — horizontally scalable.",
        "boundaries": "Owns only inference and feature assembly. Does NOT own training, evaluation, or data collection. Loads model artifacts from Model Registry at startup and on promotion signal."
      },
      {
        "name": "Feature Store",
        "responsibility": "Pre-computes and serves real-time and batch features: courier current load (real-time), zone historical averages (batch), weather conditions (near-real-time). Backed by Redis for online serving, with batch features materialized from the warehouse on a schedule.",
        "boundaries": "Owns feature computation logic and serving. Consumers (Prediction API, Training Pipeline) read from it but never write raw features directly."
      },
      {
        "name": "Training Pipeline",
        "responsibility": "Weekly batch job: pulls labeled delivery data from the data warehouse, reads historical features from the offline feature store, trains the model, evaluates against the champion model on holdout data, and publishes a candidate artifact to the Model Registry.",
        "boundaries": "Owns model training and offline evaluation. Does NOT own promotion decisions — that's the Model Registry's gate."
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Registry",
        "responsibility": "Versioned storage of model artifacts with metadata (training date, evaluation metrics, dataset hash, status: candidate/champion/retired). Enforces promotion gate: a candidate only becomes champion if evaluation metrics pass thresholds. Stores the previous champion for rollback.",
        "boundaries": "Owns model lifecycle (candidate → champion → retired). Simple: could be an S3 bucket with a metadata table in Postgres. No need for MLflow unless the team already uses it."
      },
      {
        "name": "Data Collector",
        "responsibility": "Captures actual delivery completion events and prediction logs (predicted vs actual). Writes to the data warehouse. This is the feedback loop that makes retraining meaningful.",
        "boundaries": "Owns delivery outcome ingestion. Async — writes to a queue/stream, then to warehouse. Never on the hot path."
      },
      {
        "name": "Shadow Evaluator",
        "responsibility": "After a candidate model is promoted, runs it in shadow mode alongside the champion for a configurable window (e.g., 2 hours). Compares predictions without affecting users. Triggers automatic rollback if the new model's error exceeds a threshold.",
        "boundaries": "Owns post-deployment validation. Reads from prediction logs, does NOT serve traffic directly."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Checkout Service",
        "to": "Prediction API",
        "contract": "POST /predict { weight_kg: float, distance_km: float, zone_id: string, order_time: ISO8601 } → { predicted_minutes: int, confidence_interval: [int, int], model_version: string }",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous — tightest coupling in the system, must be fast and reliable"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction API",
        "to": "Feature Store (Redis)",
        "contract": "GET features by (zone_id, courier_id, timestamp) → { zone_avg_minutes: float, courier_current_load: int, weather_code: string, zone_congestion_score: float }",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous — on the hot path, must be sub-10ms"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction API",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "On startup and on promotion webhook: fetch champion model artifact (serialized model file + feature schema version)",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous — model loaded into memory, not fetched per-request"
      },
      {
        "from": "Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Feature Store (Offline)",
        "contract": "SQL/Parquet read of historical feature vectors joined with delivery outcomes",
        "coupling_type": "batch — no latency constraint"
      },
      {
        "from": "Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "PUT candidate artifact + evaluation metrics → triggers promotion gate",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous — weekly cadence"
      },
      {
        "from": "Data Collector",
        "to": "Data Warehouse",
        "contract": "Append delivery events: { order_id, predicted_minutes, actual_minutes, features_used, model_version, timestamp }",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous — event-driven, eventual consistency"
      },
      {
        "from": "Shadow Evaluator",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "POST rollback signal if new champion's MAE exceeds threshold by >15% compared to previous champion",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous — monitoring loop"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "HOT PATH (checkout, <100ms P99): Checkout → Prediction API → [Feature Store Redis lookup ~5ms] → [In-memory model inference ~10-20ms] → Response. COLD PATH (weekly): Data Warehouse → Training Pipeline → [Feature Store offline read] → Train → Evaluate → Model Registry → [Promotion gate] → Webhook to Prediction API → Reload model in-memory. FEEDBACK LOOP (continuous): Delivery completion events → Data Collector → Queue → Data Warehouse → Available for next training run. SAFETY NET (post-deploy): Shadow Evaluator reads prediction logs for 2h after promotion → auto-rollback if degraded.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Feature Store (online/offline split)",
        "rationale": "The 100ms P99 constraint makes it impossible to compute features at request time (weather API calls, historical aggregations). Pre-computing into Redis keeps the hot path fast. The offline store ensures training uses the same feature logic (avoiding training-serving skew)."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Blue-Green Model Deployment",
        "rationale": "The business requires rollback capability. By keeping the previous champion model artifact and metadata, rollback is a metadata flip + API reload — not a redeploy. Simple and instant."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Champion-Challenger with Shadow Evaluation",
        "rationale": "Weekly retraining is risky without validation. The promotion gate catches obvious regressions offline. Shadow evaluation catches subtle distribution-shift regressions in production without impacting users."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "In-Process Model Serving",
        "rationale": "For a team of 4, a separate model serving infrastructure (TF Serving, Triton) adds operational burden without proportional benefit. Loading a LightGBM/XGBoost model directly into the API process gives sub-20ms inference with zero network hops. Revisit only if the model becomes a neural network requiring GPU."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Prediction Logging for Feedback Loop",
        "rationale": "Every prediction is logged with the features used and model version. When the actual delivery time arrives, these are joined to create labeled training data. This closes the loop and enables continuous improvement."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Delivery Prediction (Core)",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["PredictionRequest (value object: immutable feature snapshot → prediction result)", "ModelVersion (entity: versioned artifact with lifecycle states)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Feature Engineering (Supporting)",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["FeatureVector (value object: zone + courier + weather features at a point in time)", "FeatureDefinition (entity: schema and computation logic for each feature)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Training (Supporting)",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["TrainingRun (entity: dataset hash, hyperparameters, metrics, resulting artifact)", "EvaluationReport (value object: metric comparisons between candidate and champion)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Delivery Outcomes (Generic)",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["DeliveryEvent (entity: order_id + actual delivery time + metadata)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Delivery Outcomes",
        "downstream": "Model Training",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Training Pipeline consumes delivery events as-is from the warehouse, no translation needed"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Feature Engineering",
        "downstream": "Delivery Prediction",
        "relationship": "Open Host Service — Feature Store exposes a clean read API; Prediction API consumes it without coupling to feature computation internals"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Model Training",
        "downstream": "Delivery Prediction",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Training produces model artifacts conforming to a schema the Prediction API requires. Schema version is part of the artifact metadata."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Order Service (external)",
        "downstream": "Delivery Prediction",
        "relationship": "Anti-Corruption Layer — Prediction API translates order details from the checkout domain into its own feature vocabulary"
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "In-process model serving (LightGBM/XGBoost loaded in API memory) instead of dedicated model serving infrastructure",
      "gains": "Zero network hop for inference (~10-20ms), trivially meets 100ms P99, minimal operational overhead for a 4-person team, simple deployment",
      "sacrifices": "Cannot serve GPU-based neural network models, memory footprint per API instance increases, model reload requires brief warm-up",
      "alternatives_considered": ["TensorFlow Serving / Triton — rejected: operational overhead too high for team size and model complexity", "Separate model microservice — rejected: adds network hop and a service to operate for no benefit with tree-based models"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Redis for online feature store instead of a managed feature platform (Feast, Tecton, Vertex Feature Store)",
      "gains": "Sub-5ms lookups, team already likely knows Redis, no vendor lock-in, low cost",
      "sacrifices": "Must build feature computation pipelines manually, no built-in feature versioning or lineage tracking",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Feast — reasonable alternative but adds infrastructure (Feast server + materialization jobs) for features that are simple enough to manage with scheduled scripts", "DynamoDB — viable if on AWS, but Redis is faster for this access pattern"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Weekly batch retraining instead of online/incremental learning",
      "gains": "Simpler to validate, debug, and rollback. Full reproducibility. Easier to reason about model behavior.",
      "sacrifices": "Model is always up to 1 week stale. Cannot adapt instantly to sudden distribution shifts (e.g., major weather event).",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Daily retraining — considered viable as a future step; weekly is safer to start", "Online learning — rejected: much harder to validate, debug, and rollback; overkill for delivery time estimation"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Simple S3 + Postgres model registry instead of MLflow / Weights & Biases",
      "gains": "No additional infrastructure, team controls the schema, trivial to implement blue-green promotion logic",
      "sacrifices": "No experiment tracking UI, no automatic lineage graphs, must build comparison dashboards manually",
      "alternatives_considered": ["MLflow — reasonable if team wants experiment tracking UI, but adds a server to operate. Recommend adopting later if experiment volume increases."]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Model algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "Start with LightGBM (fast, interpretable, easy to serve in-process). The feature store + registry architecture is model-agnostic — swapping to XGBoost, a neural network, or an ensemble requires only changing the training pipeline and potentially the serving layer."
    },
    {
      "area": "Feature additions",
      "evolution_path": "New features (e.g., traffic data, holiday flags, promotion events) are added to the Feature Store pipeline. The Prediction API and Training Pipeline consume features by schema — adding a feature doesn't change the serving code, only the feature computation and model retraining."
    },
    {
      "area": "Retraining frequency",
      "evolution_path": "The pipeline is triggered by a scheduler. Changing from weekly to daily is a config change, not an architecture change. The promotion gate and shadow evaluator work regardless of cadence."
    },
    {
      "area": "Model serving infrastructure",
      "evolution_path": "If the team later needs GPU models or multi-model serving, the Prediction API can be refactored to call an external model server. The feature assembly logic stays in the API; only the inference call changes."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Feature Store as the single source of features",
      "reason": "Both training and serving MUST read from the same feature definitions. This rigidity prevents training-serving skew, which is the #1 cause of silent ML system failures. Never let the training pipeline compute features differently than the serving path."
    },
    {
      "area": "Promotion gate before any model serves production traffic",
      "reason": "No model reaches production without passing the evaluation gate. This is a hard constraint — even if it slows down iteration, it prevents shipping a model that predicts 3-hour deliveries as 15 minutes."
    },
    {
      "area": "Prediction logging is mandatory",
      "reason": "Every prediction must be logged with its features and model version. Without this, the feedback loop breaks and future retraining has no ground truth. This is non-negotiable infrastructure."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Training-serving skew: features computed differently in batch training vs online serving, causing silent accuracy degradation",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Single feature definition used by both online (Redis) and offline (warehouse) paths. Integration tests that verify feature parity. Log feature vectors at prediction time and compare against offline computation in CI."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Stale features in Redis causing incorrect predictions (e.g., courier load not updated, weather 6 hours old)",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Feature freshness monitoring: alert if any feature's last-updated timestamp exceeds its expected refresh interval. Courier load updated via event stream (near-real-time). Weather refreshed every 15 minutes. Zone averages refreshed hourly."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Model degradation goes undetected between weekly retraining cycles (distribution shift from seasonal changes, new zones, etc.)",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Continuous monitoring of prediction accuracy: compare predicted vs actual delivery times daily. Alert if MAE increases >20% from baseline. The shadow evaluator catches post-promotion regression, but ongoing drift monitoring catches mid-week degradation."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Redis failure takes down the checkout prediction path",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Fallback to zone-based static lookup table (precomputed averages) if Redis is unavailable. Return prediction with lower confidence flag. Redis deployed as a cluster with replicas. Circuit breaker on the Redis client with 50ms timeout."
    },
    {
      "risk": "100ms P99 budget exceeded under load spikes (Black Friday, flash sales)",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Load test the full hot path regularly. The budget breakdown: network ingress ~5ms, feature fetch ~5ms, inference ~15ms, network egress ~5ms = ~30ms typical, leaving 70ms headroom. Pre-scale API instances before known traffic events. If P99 approaches 80ms, investigate feature store latency first."
    },
    {
      "risk": "4-person team cannot sustain operational burden of too many components",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Architecture intentionally avoids heavyweight ML platforms. Total new components to operate: Prediction API (stateless, simple), Redis (managed service), one cron job (training pipeline), one S3 bucket + small Postgres table (registry). This is within a 4-person team's capacity."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Phase 1 (weeks 1-3): Prediction API + Feature Store + static model. Get the hot path working end-to-end with a hand-tuned heuristic model (distance × zone_factor). Validate P99 < 100ms in staging. Phase 2 (weeks 4-6): Training Pipeline + Model Registry. Train the first real LightGBM model on historical data. Implement promotion gate. Deploy first ML model. Phase 3 (weeks 7-8): Feedback loop + Shadow Evaluator. Wire up prediction logging, delivery outcome collection, and automated weekly retraining. Implement shadow evaluation and auto-rollback. Phase 4 (ongoing): Feature enrichment, monitoring dashboards, accuracy improvements.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "services/prediction-api/ — Stateless HTTP service (Python/FastAPI or Go). Loads model at startup, serves predictions.",
      "services/prediction-api/feature_client.py — Redis feature store client with circuit breaker and fallback",
      "services/prediction-api/model_loader.py — Loads model from registry, handles reload on promotion webhook",
      "pipelines/training/ — Weekly training job (Python). Reads from warehouse, trains LightGBM, evaluates, publishes to registry.",
      "pipelines/features/ — Feature computation jobs: batch (hourly/daily SQL), near-real-time (courier load stream processor), weather fetcher (15min cron)",
      "infrastructure/model-registry/ — S3 bucket config + Postgres schema for model metadata and lifecycle",
      "services/shadow-evaluator/ — Post-promotion monitoring job, reads prediction logs, compares champion vs previous",
      "monitoring/dashboards/ — Prediction accuracy, feature freshness, model version, P99 latency"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Use FastAPI for the Prediction API — async, fast, good for ML serving. Use LightGBM's native Python inference (no ONNX needed at this scale). Use Redis Cluster with read replicas for the feature store. Use Airflow or a simple cron + Python script for the training pipeline — do NOT over-engineer the orchestration. Use S3 versioned objects for model artifacts. Use structured logging (JSON) for all prediction logs to enable easy warehouse ingestion.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT use a separate model serving framework (TF Serving, Triton) unless you outgrow in-process serving. The operational cost is not justified for a 4-person team with tree-based models.",
      "DO NOT compute features at inference time. Every feature must be pre-computed and cached in Redis. A single weather API call at inference time blows your latency budget.",
      "DO NOT skip the offline evaluation gate. 'The model trained successfully' is not the same as 'the model is better than what's in production.'",
      "DO NOT let training and serving use different feature computation code. This is the most common and most dangerous ML system bug.",
      "DO NOT build a custom ML platform. Use simple tools: S3, Redis, Postgres, cron. You have 4 engineers, not 40.",
      "DO NOT retrain on all historical data every week. Use a rolling window (e.g., last 90 days) to let the model adapt to recent patterns without overfitting to stale data."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 85,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Hot path architecture will meet 100ms P99 — the math works: Redis ~5ms + in-process LightGBM ~15ms + overhead ~10ms = ~30ms typical",
      "Blue-green model deployment with rollback is the right pattern for weekly retraining",
      "Feature store split (online Redis / offline warehouse) is the standard and correct approach for this latency requirement",
      "The architecture is right-sized for a 4-person team — no unnecessary infrastructure"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Specific model algorithm choice (LightGBM recommended, but actual performance depends on data characteristics the team will discover during training)",
      "Feature freshness requirements for courier load — if courier state changes every few seconds, the event stream processor may need careful tuning to keep Redis consistent without overwhelming it",
      "Whether the team needs a proper experiment tracking tool (MLflow) from day one or can start without it — depends on how much experimentation the ML engineers plan to do"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The model is a tree-based ensemble (LightGBM/XGBoost), not a deep neural network requiring GPU inference",
      "Traffic volume is moderate (thousands of QPS, not hundreds of thousands) — if scale is much larger, the Prediction API needs more careful capacity planning",
      "Historical delivery data exists and is reasonably clean — if not, Phase 1 extends to include data collection and cleaning",
      "The team has access to managed Redis and S3/equivalent object storage",
      "Weather data is available via an external API with reasonable refresh rates"
    ]
  }
}
